 HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2583<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/25/02 10:29:51 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=202.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Pro's and Con's of heavy booster assisted Orion.</span><hr size=1> This is the most likely strategy we will ever see come to light for Orion in my opinion. Massive chemical boosters lift an Orion to space. Beyond the atmosphere and wailing of environmentalists to radioactive interplanetary void where it can start pulsing away. A lot of boosters would be needed for even the smallest most inefficient Orion possible I know. Is that really a prohibitive factor in lifting an Orion though. A chemical rocket is just a big tank with a nozzle at one end. Why not build some monstrous rockets which make even a Sea Dragon look insignificant. Let them expend themselves completely getting the Orion to space. On the plus side we save on pulse units. Wouldn't it be possible to choose the ideal scale of Orion vehicle needed and then just calculate the number and size of boosters necessary. They will only be big dumb 5 stage boosters. No costly habitation modules. Just giant throwaway fireworks. This is John Fraz's favourite Orion proposal. I'm just wondering how much boosting would be necessary for a 10,000 ton Orion. Maybe even a 100,000 ton version. Building big dumb boosters doesn't require rocket scientists. Just structural design engineers, a scaled up rocket schematic, moulds, work crews, a huge furnace and a factory assembly line bigger than a Hercules Aircraft hanger. China could probably manage it.     <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 481<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/26/02 12:12:41 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=202.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Pro's and Con's of heavy booster assisted Orion.</span><hr size=1> If Brad Edward's bucks everyones' predictions and actually builds and proves the technical and economic feasability of a space elevator I think it's possible that instead of using expensive and dangerous rockets we could just use an elevator.  Of course we'd have to sit around and wait until one that can carry hundreds of tons into space is built.  It would certainly be a lot cheaper going that route.  <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A> at: 11/26/02 12:13:07 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1544<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/26/02 11:51:12 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=202.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Pro's and Con's of heavy booster assisted Orion.</span><hr size=1> How about an Orion using several shuttle SRB's to boost to high altitude?<br>
<br>
&quot;The SRBs are solid rockets that provide most of the main force or thrust (71 percent) needed to lift the space shuttle off the launch pad. In addition, the SRBs support the entire weight of the space shuttle orbiter and fuel tank on the launch pad. Each SRB has the following dimensions, parameters and parts:&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>SRB Dimensions</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
 height - approximately 150 ft (46 m) <br>
 diameter - 12 ft (3.7 m) <br>
 weight: <br>
  empty - 192,000 lb (87,090 kg) <br>
  full - 1,300,000 lb (589,670 kg) <br>
 thrust - 2.65 million lb (11.7 million N) <br>
<br>
<br>
8 SRB's would weigh 10,400,000 lb<br>
and produce 21,200,000 lb thrust for a payload of <br>
10,800,000 lb or 5400 tons at 1 to 1.  So lets reduce this down to a smaller NASA spec Orion at 2,520,000 lb or 1125 tons.  This will give us a thrust to weight ratio at liftoff of 8.41 to 1.  This is overkill. Plus the SRB's burn duration is short.  So lets ignite only 4 at liftoff, drop them at altitude, then ignite the remaining 4 SRBs to boost the altitude even higher - if not orbital.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/thread_images/orion_srb2.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A> at: 11/26/02 11:55:54 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nebobgrenville>nebobgrenville</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://my.oregonstate.edu/courses/1/NE_114_X001_F2002/uploads/homepage/_1060577_1/triga.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 185<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/26/02 2:09:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=202.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Pro's and Con's of heavy booster assisted Orion.</span><hr size=1> GA actually considered using solid-propellant motors for launching their smaller lunar logistic vehicle ideas. They used an in-line cluster of six motors with a total thrust of only 11.9 million N for a T/W of 1.5:1.<br>
<br>
Using 8 STS SRBs to lift to altitude (as the shuttle does) and a second in-line liquid or solid fueled stage for orbital insertion, you could easily place masive payloads in orbit. If you can achieve a payload of 1000 tonnes, you could place a fully assembled (minus all of the fuel and destination payload) 20 m ship into orbit [operational payload (290 mT) + propulsion module (380 mT) + 600 pulse units (270 mT) + start up fluids and guidence (60 mT) =1000mT]. If improved proportional to the 10 m using the figure in the EPPP paper, the new 20 m would have an Isp of 9000s and produce 18 million N of thrust. Once fueled and loaded such a craft could go to the outer planets carring 20 men, 500+ mT of cargo and get there in record time. <p>&quot;If,&quot; he wispered, &quot;if we could only pick that lock....&quot; - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mauk2>Mauk2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 118<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/26/02 3:47:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=202.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Pro's and Con's of heavy booster assisted Orion.</span><hr size=1> LOL, this topic brings back memories.  I used to tinker a lot with heavy lift chemical boosters, albeit without the Orion upper stage.<br>
<br>
<br>
Using 8 SSRB's as a first stage will get you 5000 tons off the ground.  You want to launch the full 5000, too, because if you don't your unthrottled solids will rack up HUGE g-forces right before they burn out.<br>
<br>
So, you get 5000 tons off the ground and flying.  I would then use a liquid fueled second stage, ignited in the air, fueled with kerosene and LOX for Isp of 300-ish or the even denser kerosene and OF2 for smaller tankage and Isp of 360-ish.  Although, to be frank, efficiency is not a worry here, cheap is.<br>
<br>
Put 3000 tons into this second stage, burn it for 300 or 400 seconds or so and voila, you should be well clear of the atmosphere with a 2000 ton Orion.  It WON'T be in orbit at this point, I don't even have to run the numbers to know you are nowhere near 9km/sec deltaV with this rig, but you will be plenty high and way over the ocean, so simply start blowing off yer bombs.  Pulse good and slow, maybe one shot every 5 seconds, so as to keep things simple.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Pros?  Simple tech, well known.<br>
<br>
