raz about the SRB's and NASA</span><hr size=1> I was thinking that the tunnel would be mostly horizontal, following the Earth's curvature at a set depth, then the last few kilometers would pitch up just before the 'projectile' exited the tunnel... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 291<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/3/02 1:38:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=202.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: heavy booster assisted Orion.</span><hr size=1> Not even going to look into the evacuated tunnel thing. (how many Gs at launch? how many more at the upturn at 6km/sec velocity? How many <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>negative</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Gs when you exit the evacuated tunnel and hit the brick wall (air)? How many levels of single-point-failure catastrophic loss of the entire vehicle and launch facility and the surrounding countryside?)<br>
